## 6. Express Types (Server)

### Route Handlers
```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from 'express';

const getLaunches = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): Promise<void> => {
  try {
    const data = store.getLaunches();
    res.json(data);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
};
```

### Typed Request Params
```typescript
const getTestItems = async (
  req: Request<{ launchId: string }>,
  res: Response,
  next: NextFunction,
): Promise<void> => {
  const launchId = parseInt(req.params.launchId, 10);
  // ...
};
```

---

## 7. Constants & Enums

### Prefer Union Types or Zod Enums
```typescript
// Zod enum (shared)
export const LaunchStatusEnum = z.enum(['PASSED', 'FAILED', 'IN_PROGRESS', 'STOPPED', 'INTERRUPTED']);
export type LaunchStatus = z.infer<typeof LaunchStatusEnum>;

// Simple union
type AnalysisType = 'auto' | 'pattern' | 'uniqueError';
```

### Named Constants
```typescript
export const DEFAULT_PORT = 8080;
export const POLL_INTERVAL_HOURS = 24;
export const QUERY_STALE_TIME_MS = 2 * 60 * 1000;
```

---

## 8. Error Handling Types

```typescript
// Client
export class ApiError extends Error {
  constructor(public status: number, message: string) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'ApiError';
  }
}

// Server
type ApiErrorResponse = {
  error: string;
  details?: Array<{ path: string; message: string }>;
};
```

---

## 9. Best Practices Summary

### Do
- Define types via Zod schemas in shared package
- Import types from `@cnv-monitor/shared`
- Use `z.infer<>` instead of manual type definitions
- Use explicit return types on exports
- Use optional chaining and nullish coalescing

### Don't
- Never use `any`
- Never duplicate types across packages
- Never use `@ts-ignore`
- Never define Zod schemas in client or server when they belong in shared
